	<http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <http://model.geneontology.org/6994852c00002231> ;
	a <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Ontology> ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Node: CACNG2 | UniProt: Q9Y698 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons, CHO cells, rat/hippocampal slice culture | Perturbation: none, mut (S9A), mut (S9D), mut (S9D-delta4) | Assay: metabolic labeling, 2D-TLC phosphopeptide mapping, SDS-PAGE mobility shift, Western blot with lambda-phosphatase | Fig: 1A-B, 2A-F | Note: Stargazin phosphorylated on 9 conserved cytoplasmic Ser residues (Ser only, no Thr/Tyr); PSD fraction preferentially phosphorylated; S9A abolishes all phosphorylation; S9D mimics mobility shift; basal phosphorylation half-life ~1 hr (staurosporine, Fig 4A)"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: PPP3CA -> PPP1CA | Relation: positively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (FK506) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 4G | Note: PP2B acts partly upstream of PP1; FK506 partially blocks NMDA-induced STG dephosphorylation"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: DLG4 -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178, 17346965 | Model: rat/hippocampal slice culture, rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons, COS-7 cells | Perturbation: mut (S9D-delta4), mut (ΔC), mut (T321F/H225V compensatory pair) | Assay: paired whole-cell recording, single quantum dot tracking, mEPSC recording, co-clustering in COS-7 | Fig: Tomita 3E, Bats 2B-C, 6B-E, S3, S8 | Note: PSD-95 PDZ domain binding is required for CACNG2's synaptic receptor adaptor activity. Tomita: S9D-delta4 (phosphomimic without PDZ site) depresses AMPA EPSC instead of enhancing it (Fig 3E). Bats: ΔC drops mEPSC frequency from 1.14 to 0.04 Hz (Fig 2B-C); StargazinT321F alone drops AMPAR immobilization to 10%, rescued to 69% by compensatory PSD-95 H225V (Fig 6B); StargazinT321F only localizes to synapses when compensatory PSD-95 is present (Fig S8). PSD-95 turnover (~25% over 5 min) is much slower than Stargazin (~25% in 30s), indicating the Stargazin-PSD-95 dissociation is the rate-limiting step for AMPAR synaptic exit."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: CACNG2 -> GRIA2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 17346965 | Model: rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons, COS-7 cells | Perturbation: mut (ΔC, PDZ site deleted), mut (T321F), mut (T321F + H225V rescue) | Assay: single QD tracking, mEPSC recording, co-clustering in COS-7 | Fig: Bats 3F-J, 5A-F, 6A-E, 8A-C, S3 | Note: ΔC reduces GluR2 immobile fraction from 52% to 26% and confined time from 68% to 44% (Fig 3H-J). StargazinT321F alone drops immobilization to 10%; rescued to 69% by compensatory PSD-95 H225V (Fig 6B). FRAP crosslinking of GluR2 also immobilizes Stargazin, proving they diffuse as a complex in both synaptic and extrasynaptic membrane (Fig 8A-C). Importantly, GluR2 ΔC (lacking its own PDZ site) does NOT change lateral diffusion (Fig 5C-F), demonstrating synaptic trapping depends on Stargazin, not GluR2 C-terminus."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: PPP1CA -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly negatively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (tautomycin) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 4F | Note: PP1 mediates NMDA-induced STG dephosphorylation; tautomycin completely blocks it; Ca2+-dependent"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: PRKCA | UniProt: P17252 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none, pharmacol (GF109203X) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay, SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 5B-C | Note: PKC directly phosphorylates STG tail more efficiently than histone; GF109203X blocks STG rephosphorylation in neurons after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Node: PPP1CA | UniProt: P36873 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (tautomycin) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 4A,4F | Note: PP1 mediates both basal and NMDA-induced STG dephosphorylation; tautomycin completely blocks both
"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: CAMK2A | UniProt: Q9UQM7 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none, pharmacol (KN93) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay, SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 5B-C | Note: CaMKII directly phosphorylates purified STG C-terminal tail with efficiency comparable to GluR1 tail; KN93 blocks STG rephosphorylation in neurons after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: CACNG2 -> GRIA1 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178, 17346965 | Model: Xenopus oocytes, rat/hippocampal slice culture, rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons | Perturbation: mut (S9A), mut (S9D), mut (S9D-delta4), mut (ΔC, PDZ site deleted), mut (T321F) | Assay: two-electrode voltage clamp, paired whole-cell recording, outside-out patch, single QD tracking, mEPSC recording | Fig: Tomita 3A-E, Bats 1A-E, 2A-E, 3A-E, 4A-D | Note: Tomita: S9D enhances synaptic AMPA currents (Fig 3D); S9A does not (Fig 3C); S9DΔ4 depresses them (Fig 3E); surface trafficking unaffected by phosphorylation state (Fig 3A-B). Bats: AMPARs are reversibly trapped on PSD-95 clusters via Stargazin (immobile fraction 25% to 82%, Fig 1D); ΔC reduces GluR1 immobile fraction from 52% to 16% (Fig 3C) and synaptic dwell time from 15s to 4.9s (Fig 4C). Stargazin and GluR1-AMPARs diffuse as complexes (Fig 8)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: PPP3CA | UniProt: Q08209 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (FK506) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 4A,4G | Note: PP2B partially blocks NMDA-induced STG dephosphorylation; acts partly upstream of PP1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: PRKCA -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none (in vitro), pharmacol (GF109203X, cellular) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay (direct), SDS-PAGE mobility shift (cellular) | Fig: 5B-C | Note: Direct phosphorylation of STG tail in vitro (more efficient than histone); confirmed in neurons where GF109203X blocks rephosphorylation after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: CAMK2A -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none (in vitro), pharmacol (KN93, cellular) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay (direct), SDS-PAGE mobility shift (cellular) | Fig: 5B-C | Note: Direct phosphorylation of STG tail in vitro; confirmed in neurons where KN93 blocks rephosphorylation after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: DLG4 | UniProt: P78352 | PMID: 15664178, 17346965 | Model: rat/hippocampal slice culture, rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons | Perturbation: mut (S9D-delta4, phosphomimic lacking PDZ site), mut (ΔC, PDZ site deleted), mut (T321F/H225V compensatory pair) | Assay: paired whole-cell recording, single quantum dot tracking, mEPSC recording | Fig: Tomita 3E, Bats 1D-E, 2B-C, 6B-E, 7A-C | Note: PSD-95 clusters reversibly trap AMPARs (immobile fraction 25% to 82%, diffusion drops to 0.007 μm²/s on clusters; Bats Fig 1D-E). Stargazin is trapped on PSD-95 clusters to the same extent as AMPARs (Bats Fig 7). S9D-delta4 lacking PDZ site depresses AMPA EPSC, showing PSD-95 interaction is required for phosphorylated STG synaptic function (Tomita Fig 3E). Compensatory T321F/H225V pair rescues AMPAR immobilization from 10% to 69% (Bats Fig 6B), confirming specificity of the Stargazin-PSD-95 interaction."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title> """NMDAR-dependent recruitment of AMPA receptor to clathrin adaptor complex - Mouse
"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/contributor> "https://orcid.org/0009-0005-9047-3868"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date> "2026-03-23"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .

